    slug: "my-wudu-book",
    description: `My Wudu Book is a colourful and instructive children's Islamic book that teaches the complete procedure of wudu (ablution) — the ritual washing that Muslims perform before prayer and other acts of worship — in a format that is engaging, easy to follow, and educational for young learners. Wudu is one of the first practical Islamic skills that a child needs to learn, as it is a prerequisite for valid prayer and an act of worship in its own right that carries immense spiritual significance. This book approaches the teaching of wudu with patience and clarity, recognising that young children learn best through visual demonstrations, step-by-step instructions, and positive reinforcement. The book presents each step of the wudu in sequential order, from the initial niyyah (intention) and saying Bismillah, through washing the hands, rinsing the mouth, cleaning the nose, washing the face, washing the arms up to the elbows, wiping the head, cleaning the ears, and finally washing the feet up to the ankles. Each step is accompanied by a detailed illustration showing a child performing that particular action, with labelled arrows and annotations that highlight exactly how the washing should be done. The book teaches the correct method of performing wudu according to the Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), including the proper order of the steps, the requirement of continuity (tartib) between successive washings, and the specific Sunnah acts such as beginning with the right side and using the siwak before wudu. Important rulings are explained in simple language, such as what breaks wudu, what to do if water is scarce (tayammum), and when wudu is recommended even when it has not been broken. The book also explains the spiritual dimension of wudu, helping children understand that it is not merely a physical cleansing but a purification of the soul that prepares the believer to stand before Allah in prayer. A special section covers the dua that should be recited after completing wudu, with Arabic text, transliteration, and meaning. The book includes a wudu checklist and a certificate of achievement that children can fill out once they have learned to perform wudu independently, providing motivation and a sense of accomplishment. Suitable for children aged three to eight, My Wudu Book is an ideal resource for parents, Islamic school teachers, and madrasah instructors who are teaching young children this essential Islamic practice.`,
